# Day 15 - Permutation in String

## Problem Statement
Given two strings `s1` and `s2`, return `true` if `s2` contains a permutation of `s1`; otherwise, return `false`.

In other words, determine whether any permutation of `s1` exists as a substring of `s2`.

## Code

class Solution {
public:
    bool checkInclusion(string s1, string s2) {
        if (s2.size() < s1.size()) {
            return false;
        }

        vector<int> freq(128, 0);

        for (char c : s1) {
            freq[c]++;
        }

        int left = 0;
        int missing = s1.size();

        for (int right = 0; right < s2.size(); right++) {
            if (freq[s2[right]] > 0) {
                missing--;
            }

            freq[s2[right]]--;

            if (right - left + 1 > s1.size()) {
                if (freq[s2[left]] >= 0) {
                    missing++;
                }

                freq[s2[left]]++;
                left++;
            }

            if (right - left + 1 == s1.size() && missing == 0) {
                return true;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
};




## Time Complexity
**O(n)**

## Space Complexity
**O(1)**

## Approach
This solution uses the **Sliding Window** technique with a frequency array. First, the frequency of each character in `s1` is stored, and a variable `missing` keeps track of the number of characters still needed to form a permutation. As the window expands over `s2`, the frequency of the current character is updated, and `missing` is decreased whenever a required character is found. If the window size becomes larger than the length of `s1`, the leftmost character is removed from the window, restoring its frequency and updating `missing` if necessary. Whenever the window size equals the length of `s1` and `missing` becomes zero, it means the current window is a permutation of `s1`, so the function returns `true`. If no such window is found after the traversal, the function returns `false`.
